The perovskite thin films were deposited by PLD on silicon (911) substrates, revealing no reflexions in XRD scans that may overlap with the ones of the thin films as it is the case for commonly used transparent conducting oxides such as ITO or FTO. Since the crystal growth of the thin film is not conveyed by any epitaxial relations but is governed by means of self-organization, the actual substrate type or lattice constant is of minor significance. Preference is given to silicon compared to quartz or glass due to the well-defined surface finish and purity, which excludes the impact of inhomogeneous interfaces and therefore allows to study only the perovskite properties. In case of PLD as deposition method, the substrate material is easily interchangeable as well as deposition of additional top or bottom layers required for complete solar cell devices in the future. A KrF excimer laser (COMPex 205F, Coherent) with a wavelength of 248 nm, a pulse duration of 30 ns and a repetition rate of 5 Hz was used. The background pressure in the vacuum chamber during the deposition was approximately 1.5×10-6mbar\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
